const e=[{id:"cbt",name:"Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT)",type:"modality",founder:"Aaron Beck (1960s); Albert Ellis (REBT precursor)",theoreticalBasis:"Cognitive model: thoughts  emotions  behaviors. Maladaptive cognitions and behavioral patterns maintain psychological distress.",coreAssumptions:["Thoughts, emotions, and behaviors are interconnected","Distorted thinking patterns (cognitive distortions) contribute to emotional distress","Changing thoughts and behaviors can relieve psychological symptoms","Therapy is collaborative, structured, goal-oriented, and time-limited","Skills learned in therapy can be applied independently after treatment ends"],keyTechniques:[{name:"Cognitive Restructuring",description:"Identify and challenge automatic negative thoughts (ANTs) and replace with more balanced thinking"},{name:"Socratic Questioning",description:"Guided discovery to help client examine evidence for/against beliefs"},{name:"Behavioral Activation",description:"Schedule pleasurable and mastery activities to counter depression-driven avoidance"},{name:"Exposure Therapy",description:"Systematic desensitization by gradually confronting feared stimuli/situations"},{name:"Thought Records",description:"Structured diary to identify situation  automatic thought  emotion  evidence for/against  balanced thought"},{name:"Behavioral Experiments",description:"Test validity of beliefs by conducting real-world experiments"},{name:"Problem Solving",description:"Systematic approach to identify problems, generate solutions, evaluate, implement, review"},{name:"Relaxation Training",description:"Progressive muscle relaxation (PMR), diaphragmatic breathing"}],cognitiveDistortions:["All-or-nothing (black/white) thinking","Catastrophizing","Mind reading","Fortune telling","Emotional reasoning","Should statements","Labeling","Magnification/Minimization","Mental filter","Overgeneralization","Personalization","Discounting positives"],conditions:["Depression","Anxiety disorders","PTSD","OCD","Eating disorders","Substance use","Insomnia","Chronic pain"],evidence:"Gold standard  highest evidence base among psychotherapies. 500+ RCTs. Effect size ~0.8 for depression, ~1.0 for anxiety disorders.",duration:"1220 sessions (structured, time-limited)",format:"Individual, group, or self-guided (computerized CBT)",contraindications:"Severe cognitive impairment; acute psychosis; crisis requiring immediate stabilization",keyFacts:["Structured agenda each session; homework is essential","Collaborative empiricism  therapist and client work as a team","Downward arrow technique reveals core beliefs underlying surface thoughts","Schema therapy extends CBT to address early maladaptive schemas"],mnemonics:[{mnemonic:"ABCDE (REBT)",meaning:"Activating event  Belief  Consequence  Dispute  Effect"},{mnemonic:"TRAP  TRAC",meaning:"Trigger  Response  Avoidance Pattern  Trigger  Response  Alternative Coping"}],questions:[{id:"cbt_q1",stem:`A 28-year-old woman with depression says, "I failed one exam, so I'm a complete failure and will never succeed." Which cognitive distortion is she demonstrating?`,choices:[{id:"A",text:"Mind reading"},{id:"B",text:"Fortune telling"},{id:"C",text:"Overgeneralization"},{id:"D",text:"Emotional reasoning"},{id:"E",text:"Magnification"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:'C is CORRECT. Overgeneralization involves drawing a broad, sweeping conclusion from a single event ("one failure = total failure as a person"). This is one of the most common cognitive distortions in depression.',whyNotA:`A is INCORRECT. Mind reading involves assuming you know what others are thinking without evidence ("She must think I'm stupid").`,whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Fortune telling involves predicting a negative future outcome as if it were certain fact.",whyNotD:'D is INCORRECT. Emotional reasoning is feeling something strongly and concluding it must be true ("I feel like a failure, therefore I am one").',whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Magnification (catastrophizing) is blowing a negative event out of proportion  distinct from drawing overgeneralized conclusions.",keyTakeaway:"Overgeneralization: one event  global conclusion about self, world, or future. Common in depression."}},{id:"cbt_q2",stem:'In CBT, the technique of "Socratic questioning" is best described as:',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Directly challenging the patient's irrational beliefs"},{id:"B",text:"Using guided questions to help the patient discover alternative perspectives"},{id:"C",text:"Providing psychoeducation about cognitive distortions"},{id:"D",text:"Role-playing feared social situations"},{id:"E",text:"Progressive muscle relaxation to reduce anxiety"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. Socratic questioning (guided discovery) uses a series of probing questions to help the client examine the evidence for their beliefs and reach their own conclusions  rather than the therapist telling them they're wrong.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Directly challenging beliefs is confrontational and less effective  CBT uses collaborative empiricism.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Psychoeducation is a component of CBT but distinct from Socratic technique.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Role-playing is used in social skills training, not Socratic questioning.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. PMR is a behavioral relaxation technique, not related to Socratic method.",keyTakeaway:"Socratic questioning = guided discovery via questions. Patient arrives at insight themselves. More lasting than direct confrontation."}},{id:"cbt_q3",stem:"A patient with panic disorder is asked to deliberately hyperventilate to prove that physical symptoms alone won't cause heart attacks. This is an example of:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Systematic desensitization"},{id:"B",text:"Behavioral experiment"},{id:"C",text:"Flooding"},{id:"D",text:"Response prevention"},{id:"E",text:"Thought stopping"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:`B is CORRECT. Behavioral experiments test the validity of beliefs by conducting real-world trials. Here, the patient tests "hyperventilation  heart attack"  when the heart attack doesn't occur, the belief is disconfirmed empirically.`,whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Systematic desensitization pairs relaxation with gradual exposure to feared stimuli on a hierarchy.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Flooding is immediate, intense exposure to the most feared stimulus without gradual steps.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Response prevention prevents compulsive behaviors after exposure, used in OCD treatment.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Thought stopping was an older technique (snapping a rubber band)  largely abandoned as it can reinforce thought suppression paradoxically.",keyTakeaway:"Behavioral experiments in CBT: test beliefs empirically  disconfirmation  cognitive change. Particularly powerful for health anxiety and panic."}}]},{id:"dbt",name:"Dialectical Behavior Therapy (DBT)",type:"modality",founder:"Marsha Linehan (1991)",theoreticalBasis:"Biosocial theory: BPD and emotional dysregulation result from biological emotional sensitivity + invalidating environment. Dialectics = balancing acceptance and change.",coreAssumptions:["Patients are doing the best they can AND need to do better","Acceptance and change are both necessary (dialectical)","Behaviors have functions  understand the function to change them","Validation is essential: behavior makes sense given context","Multiple perspectives must be balanced simultaneously"],coreModules:[{name:"Mindfulness",description:'Core skill; "wise mind" (balance of emotional + rational mind); observe, describe, participate without judgment'},{name:"Distress Tolerance",description:"TIPP (Temperature, Intense exercise, Paced breathing, Paired muscle relaxation); ACCEPTS distraction; radical acceptance; crisis survival skills"},{name:"Emotion Regulation",description:"PLEASE (treat Physical illness, avoid Lethal substances, Eat balanced, Avoid mood-altering drugs, Sleep hygiene, Exercise); reduce vulnerability to emotions; opposite action"},{name:"Interpersonal Effectiveness",description:"DEAR MAN (Describe, Express, Assert, Reinforce, Mindful, Appear confident, Negotiate); GIVE (Gentle, Interested, Validate, Easy manner); FAST (Fair, Apologies minimal, Stick to values, Truthful)"}],format:"Comprehensive: individual therapy + skills group + phone coaching + therapist consultation team",conditions:["Borderline Personality Disorder (FDA-approved indication)","Suicidal/NSSI behavior","Substance use disorders","Eating disorders","Treatment-resistant depression","PTSD"],evidence:"Reduces suicidality, NSSI, hospitalizations. RCTs show 50-60% reduction in suicide attempts vs. treatment as usual in BPD.",duration:"612 months (comprehensive standard program)",keyFacts:["DBT was specifically developed for chronically suicidal individuals with BPD","Diary cards track emotions, urges, and target behaviors daily","Commitment strategies increase motivation to change","Chain analysis: functional behavioral analysis of problem behavior (antecedents  behavior  consequences)",'"Radical acceptance" = accepting reality as it is without approval or judgment'],mnemonics:[{mnemonic:"TIPP",meaning:"Temperature (cold water to face) · Intense exercise · Paced breathing · Paired muscle relaxation  distress tolerance skills"},{mnemonic:"DEAR MAN",meaning:"Describe · Express · Assert · Reinforce · Mindful · Appear confident · Negotiate  assertiveness skill"},{mnemonic:"ACCEPTS",meaning:"Activities · Contributing · Comparisons · Emotions (opposite) · Push away · Thoughts (other) · Sensations  distracting from crisis"},{mnemonic:"PLEASE",meaning:"Physical illness treatment · Lethal substances avoid · Eating balanced · Avoid mood-altering drugs · Sleep hygiene · Exercise  long-term emotion regulation"}],questions:[{id:"dbt_q1",stem:`A patient with BPD is taught to "accept the situation exactly as it is, without fighting it or wishing it were different, even if you don't like it." This DBT skill is called:`,choices:[{id:"A",text:"Mindful observation"},{id:"B",text:"Radical acceptance"},{id:"C",text:"Opposite action"},{id:"D",text:"Distress tolerance"},{id:"E",text:"Wise mind"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:'B is CORRECT. Radical acceptance is acknowledging reality completely  including painful facts  without denial, judgment, or fighting. It does NOT mean approval. It stops the suffering added by non-acceptance (the "second arrow").',whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Mindful observation is noticing experiences without judgment, but doesn't specifically address full acceptance of painful realities.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Opposite action involves acting contrary to emotion urges (e.g., approaching when afraid, activating when depressed).",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Distress tolerance is the module; radical acceptance is a specific skill within it.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Wise mind is the integration of emotion mind and reasonable mind  the balanced center of wisdom.",keyTakeaway:"Radical acceptance = accept reality as-is. Reduces suffering (resistance = pain  non-acceptance). Key DBT distress tolerance skill."}},{id:"dbt_q2",stem:'In DBT, the "TIPP" skill is used for which purpose?',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Building interpersonal effectiveness in relationships"},{id:"B",text:"Rapidly reducing intense emotional arousal in a crisis"},{id:"C",text:"Identifying and challenging unhelpful thoughts"},{id:"D",text:"Regulating emotions through behavioral activation"},{id:"E",text:"Improving mindful awareness of internal states"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. TIPP skills rapidly lower physiological arousal in crisis: Temperature (cold water activates dive reflex  slows heart), Intense exercise (burns off stress hormones), Paced breathing (activates parasympathetic), Paired muscle relaxation.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. DEAR MAN / GIVE / FAST are interpersonal effectiveness skills.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Cognitive restructuring/Socratic questioning are CBT techniques, not TIPP.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. PLEASE skill (not TIPP) focuses on long-term behavioral factors that regulate vulnerability to emotions.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Mindfulness (observe, describe, participate) addresses mindful awareness, distinct from crisis management TIPP.",keyTakeaway:"TIPP = rapid biological down-regulation in crisis. Temperature · Intense exercise · Paced breathing · Paired muscle relaxation."}}]},{id:"act",name:"Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT)",type:"modality",founder:"Steven Hayes (1986)",theoreticalBasis:"Relational Frame Theory (RFT); psychological flexibility = contacting the present moment fully, as a conscious human being, and changing or persisting in behavior when doing so serves valued ends.",coreProcesses:[{name:"Acceptance",description:"Actively embracing private experiences without unnecessary defense"},{name:"Defusion",description:'Separating from thoughts  seeing them as mental events rather than facts ("I am having the thought that..."'},{name:"Contact with Present Moment",description:"Mindful awareness of here-and-now"},{name:"Self as Context",description:'Observer self  the "sky" perspective, distinct from thoughts/feelings (the "weather")'},{name:"Values",description:"Identifying what truly matters  chosen life directions"},{name:"Committed Action",description:"Taking effective action aligned with values despite discomfort"}],keyTechniques:[{name:"Defusion Exercises",description:`"Leaves on a stream" metaphor; repeating thought until it loses meaning; "I notice I'm having the thought that..."`},{name:"Acceptance Exercises",description:'"Struggle switch"; expansion  making room for discomfort'},{name:"Values Clarification",description:"Bull's eye exercise; values compass; identifying stated vs. chosen values"},{name:"Metaphors",description:"Passengers on the bus; Chinese finger trap; person in the hole"}],conditions:["Chronic pain","Depression","Anxiety","OCD","Psychosis","Substance use","Work stress","Smoking cessation"],evidence:"Strong: 100+ RCTs. Especially efficacious for chronic pain and treatment-resistant conditions. Listed on APA Division 12 empirically supported treatments.",duration:"Variable: 816 sessions typical",keyFacts:["Goal is NOT symptom reduction per se  it's psychological flexibility","Cognitive fusion = when thoughts dictate behavior; defusion is the antidote","Experiential avoidance is the core pathological process in ACT",'"Third-wave" CBT (along with DBT, MBSR, MBCT)',"Values  goals; values are directions, goals are destinations"],questions:[{id:"act_q1",stem:'A patient with chronic pain keeps avoiding social activities because of fear the pain will worsen. The ACT therapist asks her to imagine her thoughts as "leaves floating down a stream" and observe them without attachment. This technique is called:',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Systematic desensitization"},{id:"B",text:"Cognitive restructuring"},{id:"C",text:"Cognitive defusion"},{id:"D",text:"Behavioral activation"},{id:"E",text:"Chain analysis"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:'C is CORRECT. Cognitive defusion in ACT creates distance between the person and their thoughts  treating thoughts as passing mental events rather than literal truths. The "leaves on a stream" metaphor helps patients observe thoughts without being dominated by them.',whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Systematic desensitization uses relaxation + graded exposure  a CBT/behavior therapy technique.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Cognitive restructuring (CBT) changes thought content. Defusion in ACT changes the relationship to thoughts without necessarily changing content.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Behavioral activation (CBT for depression) involves scheduling activities to improve mood.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Chain analysis (DBT) analyzes the antecedents and consequences of problem behaviors.",keyTakeaway:"Defusion = separating from thoughts (seeing them as clouds/leaves). CBT changes thought content; ACT changes relationship with thoughts."}}]},{id:"mi",name:"Motivational Interviewing (MI)",type:"modality",founder:"William Miller & Stephen Rollnick (1983)",theoreticalBasis:"Person-centered, directive method for enhancing intrinsic motivation to change by exploring and resolving ambivalence. Based on Transtheoretical Model of Change (Prochaska & DiClemente).",stagesOfChange:[{stage:"Precontemplation",description:"Not considering change; unaware of problem or resistant to it"},{stage:"Contemplation",description:"Aware there's a problem; ambivalent about change"},{stage:"Preparation",description:"Committed to change; making plans"},{stage:"Action",description:"Actively making changes"},{stage:"Maintenance",description:"Sustained change; preventing relapse"},{stage:"Relapse/Recycling",description:"Normal part of change process; return to earlier stage"}],spirit:["Collaborate (not prescribe)","Evoke (intrinsic motivation, not impose)","Autonomy support (not control)","Compassion"],coreSkills:[{name:"OARS",description:"Open-ended questions · Affirmations · Reflective listening · Summaries"},{name:"Elicit-Provide-Elicit",description:"Ask permission/interest  provide info  ask for response"},{name:"Change Talk vs. Sustain Talk",description:"Recognize and reinforce change talk (DARN-CAT: Desire, Ability, Reasons, Need, Commitment, Activation, Taking steps)"},{name:"Rolling with Resistance",description:"Avoid arguing; reflect resistance, shift perspective, explore ambivalence"}],conditions:["Substance use disorders","Weight management","Medication adherence","Chronic disease management","Smoking cessation","Health behavior change"],evidence:"Strong; 200+ RCTs. Effect size 0.7 for alcohol use, 0.8 for smoking cessation. First-line approach for ambivalent/unmotivated patients.",duration:"14 sessions (brief interventions) to ongoing (integrated into treatment)",keyFacts:["Righting reflex (urge to correct/fix) is the most common MI mistake","Confrontational approaches increase resistance and reduce change","Rolling with resistance = non-argumentative response to sustain talk","Decisional balance worksheet: pros/cons of current behavior vs. change","FRAMES acronym: Feedback · Responsibility · Advice · Menu of options · Empathy · Self-efficacy"],mnemonics:[{mnemonic:"OARS",meaning:"Open questions · Affirmations · Reflective listening · Summaries  core MI communication skills"},{mnemonic:"DARN-CAT",meaning:"Desire · Ability · Reasons · Need (preparatory change talk), Commitment · Activation · Taking steps (mobilizing change talk)"}],questions:[{id:"mi_q1",stem:'A physician says to a patient with diabetes who refuses to follow his diet: "You NEED to change your eating habits or you will lose your feet." A Motivational Interviewing expert would identify this as:',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Appropriate confrontation to create urgency"},{id:"B",text:"The righting reflex, which typically increases resistance"},{id:"C",text:"An effective use of fear appeals in health promotion"},{id:"D",text:"A good example of eliciting change talk"},{id:"E",text:"Rolling with resistance technique"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. The righting reflex is the well-intentioned but counterproductive urge of helpers to tell patients what they should do and why. It typically evokes resistance (sustain talk), not change talk. In MI, change must be elicited from within the patient.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Confrontation in MI consistently increases resistance and reduces change. MI spirit is collaborative, not confrontational.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Research shows fear appeals without self-efficacy often lead to denial or defensive avoidance, not behavior change.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Eliciting change talk means drawing out the patient's OWN reasons/desire to change  not telling them they must change.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Rolling with resistance involves non-argumentative responses to resistance  the opposite of pushing harder.",keyTakeaway:"Righting reflex = impulsive urge to fix/warn/advise. Increases resistance in ambivalent patients. MI principle: evoke intrinsic motivation, don't impose."}},{id:"mi_q2",stem:`A patient says, "I know I drink too much but I'm not sure I want to stop  alcohol helps me cope with stress." According to the Transtheoretical Model, this patient is in which stage?`,choices:[{id:"A",text:"Precontemplation"},{id:"B",text:"Contemplation"},{id:"C",text:"Preparation"},{id:"D",text:"Action"},{id:"E",text:"Maintenance"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:'B is CORRECT. Contemplation: the patient acknowledges the problem ("I know I drink too much") but is ambivalent about change. This ambivalence  seeing both pros and cons of changing  is the defining characteristic of contemplation.',whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Precontemplation: no acknowledgment of the problem or explicit denial that it's a problem. This patient acknowledges the problem.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Preparation: committed to change, making plans within the next 30 days. This patient is not committed to change.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Action: actively modifying behavior. This patient has not started changing.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Maintenance: sustained change for 6+ months, working to prevent relapse.",keyTakeaway:"Contemplation = aware of problem + ambivalent. Best MI approach: explore ambivalence using decisional balance. Elicit change talk without pushing."}}]},{id:"psychodynamic",name:"Psychodynamic Therapy",type:"modality",founder:"Sigmund Freud (psychoanalysis); modern evolution by Luborsky, Shedler, Kernberg",theoreticalBasis:"Unconscious mental processes, early childhood experiences, and relational patterns shape current psychological functioning. Insight into these patterns promotes change.",coreConceptsPsychodynamic:["Unconscious: mental processes outside awareness influencing behavior","Defense mechanisms: unconscious strategies to manage anxiety/conflict","Transference: patient's feelings toward significant others displaced onto therapist","Countertransference: therapist's emotional reactions to patient (must be monitored/managed)","Object relations: internalized representations of self and others","Attachment patterns: influence on adult relationships"],defenseMechanisms:{mature:["Sublimation","Altruism","Humor","Suppression (conscious)"],neurotic:["Repression","Rationalization","Intellectualization","Displacement","Reaction formation","Isolation of affect"],immature:["Projection","Splitting","Acting out","Passive aggression","Somatization","Regression","Denial"],psychotic:["Distortion","Delusional projection","Psychotic denial"]},keyTechniques:[{name:"Free Association",description:"Patient says whatever comes to mind without censoring"},{name:"Dream Analysis",description:"Exploring manifest vs. latent content of dreams"},{name:"Interpretation",description:"Therapist offers insights connecting unconscious material to current issues"},{name:"Transference Analysis",description:"Examining patient's feelings/reactions to the therapist as window into relational patterns"},{name:"CCRT",description:"Core Conflictual Relationship Theme  wish, response of other, response of self"}],conditions:["Depression","Anxiety","Personality disorders","Somatic disorders","Relational difficulties","Character pathology"],evidence:"Moderate; Shedler (2010) meta-analysis: effect size 0.97, comparable to CBT. Gains continue after therapy ends (sleeper effect).",duration:"Short-term (1625 sessions) to long-term/open-ended analysis",keyFacts:["Therapeutic alliance is the core vehicle of change","Insight is necessary but not sufficient  must be emotionally experienced (not just intellectual)","Brief (STPP) focuses on one core conflict vs. long-term analysis covering broader characterological issues","Mentalization-based therapy (MBT) is a psychodynamic approach for BPD"],questions:[{id:"psych_q1",stem:'A medical student who unconsciously resents patients describes in supervision that she "finds ward rounds intellectually stimulating as a chance to apply biochemistry." This defense mechanism is:',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Sublimation"},{id:"B",text:"Rationalization"},{id:"C",text:"Intellectualization"},{id:"D",text:"Reaction formation"},{id:"E",text:"Projection"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:'C is CORRECT. Intellectualization: the emotional component is removed by focusing only on the intellectual/abstract aspects of a situation. The student focuses on the "biochemistry" to avoid experiencing her actual negative feelings about patients.',whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Sublimation redirects an impulse into a socially acceptable activity (e.g., channeling aggression into competitive sports). No such channeling here.",whyNotB:`B is INCORRECT. Rationalization creates logical-sounding post-hoc justifications for behavior motivated by unacceptable reasons (e.g., "I wasn't late, I was giving others time to prepare").`,whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Reaction formation transforms an unacceptable impulse into its opposite (e.g., excessive niceness masking hatred).",whyNotE:`E is INCORRECT. Projection attributes one's own unacceptable feelings to others (e.g., "The patients don't like me").`,keyTakeaway:"Intellectualization = isolation of affect + focusing on abstract/cognitive dimension. Common in medical training. Compare: rationalization (justification) vs. intellectualization (abstraction)."}}]},{id:"emdr",name:"Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing (EMDR)",type:"modality",founder:"Francine Shapiro (1987)",theoreticalBasis:"Adaptive Information Processing (AIP) model: trauma memories stored in non-adaptive, fragmented form; bilateral stimulation facilitates associative connections and adaptive resolution.",protocol8Phases:["History taking & treatment planning","Preparation (resources, stabilization)","Assessment (target memory, negative cognition, positive cognition, emotion, SUDS, body sensation)","Desensitization (bilateral stimulation while holding trauma memory)","Installation (strengthen positive cognition)","Body scan (check for residual somatic distress)","Closure","Reevaluation"],bilateralStimulation:["Horizontal eye movements (therapist finger tracking)","Auditory tones (alternating)","Tactile taps (alternating hands)"],conditions:["PTSD (first-line; WHO, NICE guidelines)","Complex trauma","Phobias","Anxiety","Grief","Performance anxiety"],evidence:"Strong  equivalent to Trauma-Focused CBT (TF-CBT) for PTSD. Endorsed by WHO, NICE, VA/DoD guidelines as first-line PTSD treatment.",duration:"612 sessions for single-incident trauma; longer for complex trauma",keyFacts:["SUDS = Subjective Units of Distress Scale (010)","VOC = Validity of Cognition scale (17, how true does positive belief feel)","Mechanism of action debated: some evidence bilateral stimulation unique; others suggest exposure/working memory taxing","No trauma narrative required (unlike exposure therapies)","Contraindications: active psychosis, severe dissociation, medical instability"],questions:[{id:"emdr_q1",stem:"EMDR is endorsed as a first-line treatment for PTSD by multiple international guidelines. Its proposed mechanism involves:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Systematic desensitization via progressive muscle relaxation"},{id:"B",text:"Facilitating adaptive reprocessing of traumatic memories through bilateral stimulation"},{id:"C",text:"Exposing patients to trauma triggers without safety signals"},{id:"D",text:"Challenging maladaptive thoughts with Socratic questioning"},{id:"E",text:"Increasing dopaminergic transmission in the prefrontal cortex"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. EMDR's Adaptive Information Processing model proposes that bilateral stimulation (eye movements, tones, taps) facilitates the brain's natural information processing system to integrate traumatic memories  connecting them to adaptive memory networks.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Systematic desensitization uses hierarchical exposure with relaxation  developed by Wolpe, distinct from EMDR.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Prolonged Exposure (PE) requires trauma narration and in-vivo exposure. EMDR does not require detailed trauma narrative.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Socratic questioning is CBT technique. EMDR uses bilateral stimulation, not cognitive restructuring dialogue.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. EMDR is a psychotherapy, not a pharmacological intervention.",keyTakeaway:"EMDR: bilateral stimulation  adaptive reprocessing  trauma memory integration. First-line PTSD treatment (WHO/NICE/VA-DoD). No trauma narrative required."}}]},{id:"person_centered",name:"Person-Centered Therapy (PCT)",type:"modality",founder:"Carl Rogers (1940s50s)",theoreticalBasis:"Humanistic: people have an innate actualizing tendency toward growth. Psychological distress arises from conditions of worth imposed by others, creating incongruence between real self and ideal self.",coreConditions:[{name:"Unconditional Positive Regard (UPR)",description:"Accepting the client completely, without judgment"},{name:"Empathy",description:`Accurately sensing and reflecting the client's felt experience ("accurate empathic understanding")`},{name:"Congruence/Genuineness",description:"Therapist is authentic and transparent  no facade"}],theoreticalConcepts:["Actualizing tendency: inherent drive toward growth","Self-concept vs. organismic experience (incongruence = distress)","Conditions of worth: internalized messages that love is conditional","Fully functioning person: open to experience, existential living, self-trust"],conditions:["Depression","Anxiety","Life transitions","Adjustment disorders","Relational difficulties","Personal growth"],evidence:"Moderate; well-supported as common factor in all good therapy. Rogers' facilitative conditions predict outcomes across all therapy modalities.",keyFacts:["Rogers advocated that therapeutic relationship itself is curative  not techniques","Non-directive: therapist follows client's lead",'Focusing (Gendlin) is an extension  connecting with bodily "felt sense"',"Emotion-Focused Therapy (EFT) is a contemporary evolution of PCT","Rogers' core conditions now recognized as necessary (though perhaps not sufficient) for all effective therapy"],questions:[{id:"pct_q1",stem:"A therapist who accepts her client's feelings and experiences completely, without judgment or evaluation  regardless of how problematic those feelings seem  is demonstrating:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Therapeutic neutrality"},{id:"B",text:"Unconditional positive regard"},{id:"C",text:"Congruence"},{id:"D",text:"Empathic accuracy"},{id:"E",text:"Therapeutic alliance"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. Unconditional positive regard (UPR) is Carl Rogers' core condition of accepting and valuing the client completely as a person, without placing conditions or judgments on their worth. UPR  approval of behavior; it's acceptance of the PERSON.",whyNotA:`A is INCORRECT. Therapeutic neutrality is a psychoanalytic concept (analyst is a "blank screen")  distinct from Rogers' UPR.`,whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Congruence refers to therapist genuineness/authenticity  their inner experience matching their outward expression.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Empathic accuracy refers to how precisely the therapist understands the client's emotional experience.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. The therapeutic alliance is the collaborative working relationship; UPR is the specific Rogers condition being described.",keyTakeaway:"Rogers' 3 core conditions: UPR (acceptance without judgment) + Empathy (accurate feeling) + Congruence (authenticity). All necessary for therapeutic growth."}}]},{id:"mdd",name:"Major Depressive Disorder (MDD)",type:"condition",icd10:"F32F33",dsmCriteria:{required:"5 of the following symptoms for 2 weeks, representing a change from previous functioning; at least one must be depressed mood OR loss of interest:",symptoms:["Depressed mood most of the day, nearly every day","Markedly diminished interest or pleasure (anhedonia)","Significant weight change (>5% in one month) or appetite change","Insomnia or hypersomnia","Psychomotor agitation or retardation (observable by others)","Fatigue or loss of energy","Feelings of worthlessness or excessive/inappropriate guilt","Diminished concentration or indecisiveness","Recurrent thoughts of death or suicidal ideation/plan/attempt"],exclusions:"Not due to substance, medical condition, or better explained by another disorder (e.g., bereavement)"},epidemiology:{lifetime:"15-20%",female:"2:1 female predominance",onset:"Mean age ~32 years; can occur at any age"},neurobiology:["Monoamine hypothesis: serotonin (5-HT), norepinephrine (NE), dopamine","Increased HPA axis activity  elevated cortisol","Neuroinflammation: elevated IL-6, CRP, TNF-","Hippocampal neurogenesis deficit (explains delayed antidepressant response)","Default mode network hyperactivity (rumination)"],treatment:{firstLine:"SSRIs (fluoxetine, sertraline, escitalopram) + psychotherapy (CBT)",secondLine:"SNRIs, bupropion, mirtazapine, TCAs, MAOIs",augmentation:"Lithium, atypical antipsychotics (aripiprazole, quetiapine), thyroid hormone",severe:"ECT (gold standard for severe/refractory/psychotic depression, suicidal emergency)",other:"Ketamine IV (rapid onset, refractory cases); TMS; psychotherapy"},antidepressantTimeline:"Response: 48 weeks; full therapeutic effect: 612 weeks",psychotherapy:["CBT (first-line)","IPT (Interpersonal therapy)","Behavioral Activation","Problem-solving therapy","MBCT (relapse prevention)"],keyFacts:["SIG E CAPS: Sleep ( or ) · Interest () · Guilt/worthlessness · Energy () · Concentration () · Appetite ( or ) · Psychomotor changes · Suicidality","ECT: 80-90% response rate  most effective acute treatment for severe MDD","Treatment-resistant depression (TRD): failure of 2 adequate antidepressant trials","Maintain treatment 6-12 months after first episode; 2+ years or indefinite after recurrent episodes","Postpartum depression: onset within 4 weeks of delivery; brucellamine/SSRIs; ECT if severe"],mnemonics:[{mnemonic:"SIG E CAPS",meaning:"Sleep fluctuation · Interest loss (anhedonia) · Guilt · Energy loss · Concentration loss · Appetite change · Psychomotor change · Suicidal ideation"},{mnemonic:"SSRI start weeks",meaning:"4 weeks: initial response; 8 weeks: adequate trial; 6 months: continuation; 2 years: maintenance for recurrent"}],questions:[{id:"mdd_q1",stem:'A 34-year-old woman presents with 3 weeks of depressed mood, inability to enjoy her hobbies (anhedonia), hypersomnia, weight gain of 5 lbs, fatigue, excessive guilt about being "a bad mother," and difficulty concentrating at work. She denies suicidal ideation. She drinks 1 glass of wine weekly. TSH is normal. Which diagnosis is MOST appropriate?',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia)"},{id:"B",text:"Bipolar II disorder, depressive episode"},{id:"C",text:"Major depressive disorder"},{id:"D",text:"Adjustment disorder with depressed mood"},{id:"E",text:"Hypothyroidism-induced depression"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. MDD: 5 DSM-5 symptoms for 2 weeks, including at least depressed mood AND/OR anhedonia. She has: depressed mood + anhedonia + hypersomnia + weight gain + fatigue + guilt + concentration problems = 7 symptoms for 3 weeks. TSH is normal (excludes hypothyroidism). Alcohol use is minimal.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Persistent Depressive Disorder (dysthymia) requires depressed mood for 2 YEARS with 2 months symptom-free periods. 3 weeks does not meet this criterion.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Bipolar II requires at least one hypomanic episode (4 days). There is no history of hypomanic or manic episodes given.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Adjustment disorder: symptoms arise within 3 months of an identifiable stressor and do NOT meet criteria for another mood disorder. No specific stressor is mentioned, and symptom count meets MDD.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. TSH is normal, ruling out hypothyroidism as the cause. Always check TSH in new-onset depression, but this patient's depression is primary.",keyTakeaway:"MDD requires 5 SIG E CAPS symptoms  2 weeks. Must include depressed mood AND/OR anhedonia. Rule out medical causes (TSH), bipolar history, and adjustment disorder."}},{id:"mdd_q2",stem:"A patient with MDD is started on sertraline. After 2 weeks, he reports no improvement. The most appropriate response is:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Switch to a different antidepressant class immediately"},{id:"B",text:"Add a second antidepressant for augmentation"},{id:"C",text:"Increase the dose and continue for a total of 48 weeks before evaluating response"},{id:"D",text:"Consider electroconvulsive therapy as the next step"},{id:"E",text:"Discontinue medication and start CBT alone"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. Antidepressants require 48 weeks for initial response assessment. After 2 weeks is too early to declare failure. The appropriate steps: ensure adequate dose  wait 4-8 weeks  if partial response, increase dose  wait another 4 weeks  if no response, switch or augment.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. 2 weeks is insufficient time to evaluate response. Switching too early means patients may never receive an adequate trial of any individual medication.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Augmentation is appropriate for partial response after an adequate trial (typically 4-8 weeks at therapeutic dose), not at 2 weeks.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. ECT is reserved for severe/refractory depression after multiple failed trials or in life-threatening situations (severe suicidality, psychotic depression, refusal to eat). This is too early.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Discontinuing medication after only 2 weeks is inappropriate unless there are severe side effects or safety concerns.",keyTakeaway:"Antidepressant timeline: 2-4 weeks (early signs)  4-8 weeks (adequate response assessment)  6-12 months (continuation)  2+ years/indefinite (recurrent). Never declare failure before 4-8 weeks at therapeutic dose."}},{id:"mdd_q3",stem:"Which antidepressant mechanism is CORRECTLY matched?",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Bupropion  serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (SNRI)"},{id:"B",text:"Mirtazapine  selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor (SSRI)"},{id:"C",text:"Venlafaxine  serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (SNRI)"},{id:"D",text:"Fluoxetine  norepinephrine-dopamine reuptake inhibitor (NDRI)"},{id:"E",text:"Trazodone  monoamine oxidase inhibitor (MAOI)"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. Venlafaxine (Effexor) inhibits reuptake of both serotonin AND norepinephrine  classic SNRI. Other SNRIs: duloxetine, levomilnacipran, desvenlafaxine.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Bupropion (Wellbutrin) is an NDRI (norepinephrine-dopamine reuptake inhibitor). No significant serotonergic activity. Unique advantages: weight-neutral, no sexual side effects, helpful for smoking cessation.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Mirtazapine (Remeron) is a NaSSA  Noradrenergic and Specific Serotonergic Antidepressant. Blocks 2-autoreceptors + 5-HT2 + 5-HT3 receptors. Causes sedation and weight gain (antihistamine effect).",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Fluoxetine (Prozac) is an SSRI  selectively blocks serotonin (5-HT) reuptake. Not dopaminergic.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Trazodone is a SARI (serotonin antagonist and reuptake inhibitor). Often used for insomnia in depression. MAOIs include phenelzine, tranylcypromine, selegiline.",keyTakeaway:"SSRI: fluoxetine/sertraline/escitalopram. SNRI: venlafaxine/duloxetine. NDRI: bupropion. NaSSA: mirtazapine. SARI: trazodone. TCA: amitriptyline/nortriptyline. MAOI: phenelzine."}}]},{id:"gad",name:"Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD)",type:"condition",icd10:"F41.1",dsmCriteria:{required:"Excessive anxiety and worry (apprehensive expectation) occurring more days than not for 6 months about multiple events/activities",symptoms:["Difficulty controlling the worry",'3 of: restlessness/feeling on edge, easily fatigued, difficulty concentrating ("mind going blank"), irritability, muscle tension, sleep disturbance',"(Note: only 1 symptom needed for children)"],impairment:"Causes clinically significant distress or functional impairment",exclusions:"Not attributable to substances, medical conditions, or better explained by another mental disorder"},epidemiology:{lifetime:"5.7%",female:"2:1 female:male",onset:"Chronic, often lifelong; mean age 30s"},neurobiology:["Amygdala hyperactivity + prefrontal cortex inhibition failure","Noradrenergic and GABAergic dysregulation","HPA axis overactivation","Intolerance of uncertainty (cognitive model key factor)"],treatment:{psychotherapy:"CBT (first-line); specifically targeting worry, intolerance of uncertainty, and avoidance",firstLinePharma:"SSRIs (escitalopram, paroxetine, sertraline) or SNRIs (venlafaxine, duloxetine)",secondLine:"Buspirone (anxiolytic, non-habit forming; delayed onset ~2-4 weeks), TCAs",shortTerm:"Benzodiazepines (short-term only; risk of dependence)",other:"Pregabalin (Europe; FDA-approved for neuropathic pain, anxiolytic off-label), hydroxyzine"},keyFacts:[`Worry is "ego-syntonic" in GAD  patient feels it's their nature, not a symptom`,'Metacognitive beliefs: "worrying keeps me safe" vs. "my worry is uncontrollable"',"Co-morbid with depression in >50% of cases","Buspirone: takes 2-4 weeks to work; no abuse potential; good for long-term GAD management","Benzodiazepines: immediate relief but risks dependence, cognitive impairment, rebound anxiety"],mnemonics:[{mnemonic:"FRIDGE (GAD symptoms)",meaning:'Fatigue · Restlessness · Irritability · Difficulty concentrating · G (muscle tension with G = "tight gut" memory hook) · Easy to wake/sleep problems'}],questions:[{id:"gad_q1",stem:"A 42-year-old accountant worries constantly about finances, her children's health, work deadlines, and global events. She has had these worries for 18 months, finds them difficult to control, experiences muscle tension, fatigue, and poor sleep. She denies panic attacks or phobias. The most likely diagnosis is:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Panic disorder"},{id:"B",text:"Specific phobia"},{id:"C",text:"Generalized Anxiety Disorder"},{id:"D",text:"Social anxiety disorder"},{id:"E",text:"OCD"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. GAD hallmark: excessive, difficult-to-control worry about MULTIPLE life domains (not just one specific fear) for 6 months + 3 somatic symptoms (muscle tension + fatigue + sleep disturbance). Duration 18 months meets criterion.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Panic disorder: recurrent unexpected panic attacks + anticipatory anxiety. No panic attacks described.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Specific phobia: anxiety circumscribed to one specific object/situation. Here, worry spans multiple domains.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Social anxiety disorder: fear of social scrutiny/embarrassment in social situations. Not described.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. OCD: intrusive ego-dystonic obsessions + compulsions. GAD worry is more realistic (though excessive); OCD obsessions are recognized as intrusive/unwanted. No compulsions described.",keyTakeaway:"GAD = multi-domain excessive worry  6 months + difficulty controlling + 3 somatic symptoms. Key feature: worry spans life, not one fixed object/situation."}}]},{id:"ptsd",name:"Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD)",type:"condition",icd10:"F43.1",dsmCriteria:{required:"Exposure to actual or threatened death, serious injury, or sexual violence (directly experienced, witnessed, learned happened to close person, or repeated/extreme exposure to details)",clusters:[{cluster:"B  Intrusion",symptoms:["Intrusive memories/flashbacks","Nightmares","Psychological/physiological reactivity to trauma cues"]},{cluster:"C  Avoidance",symptoms:["Avoidance of internal memories/thoughts","Avoidance of external reminders"]},{cluster:"D  Negative cognitions/mood",symptoms:["Inability to remember key aspect of trauma","Persistent negative beliefs about self/world","Distorted blame of self or others","Persistent negative emotions","Diminished interest","Detachment/estrangement","Inability to experience positive emotions (emotional numbing)"]},{cluster:"E  Arousal/reactivity",symptoms:["Irritability/aggression","Reckless/self-destructive behavior","Hypervigilance","Exaggerated startle","Concentration problems","Sleep disturbance"]}],duration:"1 month (if <1 month = Acute Stress Disorder)"},subtypes:["With dissociative symptoms (derealization/depersonalization)","With delayed expression (6 months after trauma)"],epidemiology:{lifetime:"8-12%",female:"2:1 female predominance; higher rate in combat veterans"},treatment:{psychotherapy:['CPT (Cognitive Processing Therapy)  first-line; challenges "stuck points" about trauma meaning',"Prolonged Exposure (PE)  first-line; imaginal + in-vivo exposure","EMDR  first-line (equivalent to TF-CBT)","DBT for PTSD + BPD"],pharmacotherapy:["Sertraline  FDA approved","Paroxetine  FDA approved","SSRIs generally: first-line pharma","Prazosin  for PTSD nightmares (1-blocker  reduces noradrenergic hyperactivation)","Venlafaxine  second-line","AVOID: benzodiazepines (not helpful for PTSD; may worsen outcomes)"]},keyFacts:['DSM-5 moved PTSD out of anxiety disorders  "Trauma and Stressor-Related Disorders"',"Acute Stress Disorder: 3 days1 month after trauma; if >1 month = PTSD","Moral injury: trauma from witnessing/participating in events violating moral code","Complex PTSD (ICD-11, not DSM-5): includes affect dysregulation, self-perception disturbances","Fear conditioning model: trauma = CS paired with threat response  generalized fear"],mnemonics:[{mnemonic:"PTSD clusters: ICAN",meaning:"Intrusion (cluster B) · Constriction avoidance (cluster C) · Alterations cognition/mood (cluster D) · Arousal/reactivity (cluster E)"}],questions:[{id:"ptsd_q1",stem:"A 28-year-old combat veteran reports recurrent nightmares about an IED explosion, avoids watching war movies or news, feels emotionally numb and detached from family, has difficulty sleeping and is hypervigilant. Symptoms began 3 months ago. The MOST indicated pharmacotherapy is:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Lorazepam 1mg TID"},{id:"B",text:"Haloperidol 2mg daily"},{id:"C",text:"Sertraline 50-200mg daily"},{id:"D",text:"Lithium 300mg TID"},{id:"E",text:"Methylphenidate 20mg daily"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. Sertraline is FDA-approved for PTSD  one of two approved medications (with paroxetine). SSRIs are first-line pharmacotherapy for PTSD. Duration of symptoms (3 months) meets PTSD criterion (1 month).",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Benzodiazepines are CONTRAINDICATED in PTSD. They may impair fear extinction, worsen dissociation, create dependence, and are not effective for core PTSD symptoms. VA/DoD guidelines specifically recommend AGAINST benzodiazepines for PTSD.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Antipsychotics are not first-line for PTSD. May be considered for severe dissociation or psychotic features, but not as initial therapy.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Lithium is used for bipolar disorder mood stabilization. No indication for PTSD.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Stimulants are not indicated for PTSD (unless comorbid ADHD). May worsen hyperarousal symptoms.",keyTakeaway:"PTSD pharmacotherapy: Sertraline or paroxetine (FDA-approved SSRIs). Consider prazosin for nightmares. AVOID benzodiazepines. Combine with trauma-focused psychotherapy (CPT, PE, or EMDR)."}},{id:"ptsd_q2",stem:"Which feature distinguishes Acute Stress Disorder from PTSD?",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Presence of dissociative symptoms"},{id:"B",text:"Duration of symptoms (3 days1 month vs. >1 month)"},{id:"C",text:"Type of traumatic exposure required"},{id:"D",text:"Response to SSRI treatment"},{id:"E",text:"Severity of flashbacks and nightmares"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. The key distinction: Acute Stress Disorder (ASD) = symptoms ranging from 3 DAYS to 1 MONTH after trauma. PTSD = symptoms persisting 1 MONTH after trauma. Both can include dissociation, intrusion, avoidance, and hyperarousal symptoms.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Dissociative symptoms can occur in both ASD and PTSD (DSM-5 PTSD has a dissociative subtype). ASD does emphasize dissociation more, but it's not the distinguishing feature.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Both ASD and PTSD require the same type of traumatic exposure (DSM-5 Criterion A: actual/threatened death, serious injury, or sexual violence).",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Both may respond to SSRIs; treatment response should not define the diagnostic distinction.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Symptom severity does not distinguish ASD from PTSD  duration is the key criterion.",keyTakeaway:"ASD: 3 days1 month post-trauma. PTSD: 1 month post-trauma. Both require Criterion A trauma exposure. About 50% of ASD cases convert to PTSD."}}]},{id:"ocd",name:"Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)",type:"condition",icd10:"F42",dsmCriteria:{required:"Obsessions, compulsions, or both. Time-consuming (>1 hr/day) or cause distress/impairment.",obsessions:"Recurrent, persistent, intrusive, unwanted thoughts/urges/images causing anxiety; person attempts to suppress/neutralize",compulsions:"Repetitive behaviors or mental acts person feels driven to perform in response to obsession or rigid rules, aimed at preventing/reducing distress or feared event (not realistically connected or excessive)"},commonThemes:[{theme:"Contamination",compulsion:"Washing, cleaning"},{theme:"Symmetry/Order",compulsion:"Arranging, counting, repeating"},{theme:"Harm",compulsion:"Checking (stove, locks)"},{theme:"Taboo thoughts (sexual, religious, aggressive)",compulsion:"Mental rituals, reassurance seeking, avoidance"}],epidemiology:{lifetime:"2-3%",onset:"Mean age ~20; bimodal: adolescence and adult"},treatment:{firstLine:"ERP  Exposure and Response Prevention (gold standard psychotherapy)",pharmacotherapy:"SSRIs (first-line: fluoxetine, fluvoxamine, sertraline, paroxetine); higher doses typically needed than for depression",clomipramine:"TCA with strong anti-obsessional properties; second-line due to side effect profile",refractory:"Augmentation with antipsychotics (risperidone, aripiprazole); DBS (deep brain stimulation)"},erpPrinciples:["Exposure: deliberate contact with feared stimulus/obsession without performing compulsion","Response Prevention: refraining from compulsive behavior after exposure","Habituation: anxiety decreases naturally over time with sustained exposure","Hierarchy: start with easier items, work up (SUDS-based)"],keyFacts:["OCD is ego-dystonic: patient recognizes obsessions as irrational/excessive (cf. OCD-spectrum: ego-syntonic)","SSRIs for OCD: higher doses and longer trial (8-12 weeks) than for depression","Clomipramine most effective TCA for OCD but anticholinergic + cardiac side effects limit use","Insight specifier: good/fair insight, poor insight, absent insight/delusional beliefs",'"OCD-spectrum disorders": BDD, hoarding disorder, trichotillomania, excoriation (skin-picking), illness anxiety',"Formal exclusion: not due to medical condition, substance, or better explained by another disorder"],questions:[{id:"ocd_q1",stem:'A 24-year-old student spends 3-4 hours daily checking whether she left the stove on or the door unlocked. She knows intellectually that she checked these things, but feels compelled to check again because "something terrible might happen." She finds these thoughts intrusive and distressing. The first-line psychotherapy for this condition is:',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Cognitive restructuring to challenge catastrophic thoughts"},{id:"B",text:"Exposure and Response Prevention (ERP)"},{id:"C",text:"Dialectical Behavior Therapy"},{id:"D",text:"EMDR for traumatic memories"},{id:"E",text:"Insight-oriented psychodynamic therapy"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. ERP (Exposure and Response Prevention) is the gold-standard behavioral treatment for OCD. She is exposed to the feared stimulus (leaving without checking) and prevented from performing the compulsion (returning to check)  anxiety habituates naturally over time.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. While CBT cognitive components can help, pure cognitive restructuring without behavioral (ERP) component is less effective for OCD. The compulsions maintain the disorder behaviorally; ERP directly targets this.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. DBT is designed for BPD and emotional dysregulation, not OCD.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. EMDR is for PTSD trauma processing. OCD is not based on discrete traumatic memories (though onset may be related to stress).",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Psychodynamic therapy has weak evidence for OCD. Insight-based approaches may even reinforce over-analysis of obsessional content.",keyTakeaway:"OCD first-line: ERP (psychotherapy) + SSRIs (pharmacotherapy). ERP principle: expose to trigger  prevent compulsion  let anxiety habituate naturally."}}]},{id:"bipolar",name:"Bipolar Disorder",type:"condition",icd10:"F31",types:{bipolar1:"At least one MANIC episode (may or may not have depressive episodes). Manic episode must last 7 days (or hospitalized/psychotic). Full criteria for mania = Bipolar I regardless of depression.",bipolar2:"At least one HYPOMANIC episode (4 days) + at least one MAJOR DEPRESSIVE episode. NO full manic episodes. Often misdiagnosed as unipolar depression.",cyclothymia:"Numerous hypomanic periods + numerous depressive periods (not meeting MDD criteria) for 2 years. No episodes meeting full criteria for either episode."},manicEpisodeCriteria:{required:"Distinct period of abnormally and persistently elevated/expansive/irritable mood + increased goal-directed activity or energy for 7 days (or any duration if hospitalized)",symptoms:"3 of DIGFAST (or 4 if mood is only irritable)",impairment:"Marked impairment, hospitalization, or psychotic features"},digfast:["Distractibility","Impulsivity/Indiscretion","Grandiosity","Flight of ideas","Activity increase","Sleep decreased (need less sleep without fatigue)","Talkativeness (pressured speech)"],treatment:{acuteMania:"Lithium + antipsychotic (aripiprazole, olanzapine, quetiapine, risperidone) OR valproate + antipsychotic",maintenance:"Lithium (gold standard  reduces suicidality + mood episodes), valproate, lamotrigine (especially for bipolar depression)",bipolarDepression:"Quetiapine, lurasidone, OFC (olanzapine-fluoxetine), lamotrigine. AVOID antidepressants monotherapy (risk of switching to mania/cycling)",avoid:"Antidepressant monotherapy in bipolar (triggers mania/mixed features/rapid cycling)"},lithiumMonitoring:{therapeutic:"0.81.2 mEq/L (acute mania); 0.60.8 mEq/L (maintenance)",toxic:">1.5 mEq/L  toxicity (TREMOR: Tremor, Renal failure, Encephalopathy, Myoclonus/movement, Oliguric, Rigidity)",monitoring:"TSH (hypothyroidism), creatinine (nephrogenic DI), serum levels q3-6 months",interactions:"NSAIDs, thiazide diuretics, ACE inhibitors increase lithium levels"},keyFacts:["Bipolar I: manic episode sufficient for diagnosis (depression not required)","Bipolar II: commonly misdiagnosed as unipolar MDD (ask about hypomanic episodes)","Lithium: only mood stabilizer proven to reduce suicide risk","Lamotrigine: NOT effective for acute mania but excellent for bipolar depression prevention","Antidepressant monotherapy in bipolar  can induce mania, mixed features, or rapid cycling","Mixed features: meets criteria for mood episode (mania or depression) PLUS 3 symptoms of opposite polarity"],mnemonics:[{mnemonic:"DIGFAST",meaning:"Distractibility · Impulsivity · Grandiosity · Flight of ideas · Activity · Sleep · Talkativeness (pressured speech)  manic symptoms"}],questions:[{id:"bipolar_q1",stem:"A 22-year-old woman was previously diagnosed with major depression following 3 depressive episodes. She now presents with 5 days of decreased need for sleep (feeling rested after 3 hours), pressured speech, inflated self-esteem, and impulsive spending. She has not required hospitalization. The MOST accurate diagnosis is:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Bipolar I disorder"},{id:"B",text:"Bipolar II disorder"},{id:"C",text:"Cyclothymia"},{id:"D",text:"Major Depressive Disorder with agitation"},{id:"E",text:"Substance-induced mood disorder"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. Bipolar II: at least one HYPOMANIC (not full manic) episode + at least one MDE. Hypomania = 4 days + DIGFAST symptoms + no hospitalization/psychosis/severe impairment. She has 5 days of hypomanic symptoms + history of 1 MDE. No hospitalization = doesn't meet Bipolar I manic criteria.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Bipolar I requires a full MANIC episode: 7 days OR hospitalized OR psychotic features. She has 5 days, no hospitalization, no psychosis  hypomanic, not manic  Bipolar II, not I.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Cyclothymia: chronic hypomanic and depressive periods (not meeting full MDE criteria) for 2 years. She has full MDE criteria (3 depressive episodes).",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Agitation in MDD does not include decreased sleep need, grandiosity, or pressured speech  these point to a mood elevation episode.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. No substance use is mentioned. In clinical practice, always rule out stimulants, but the question focuses on the clinical presentation.",keyTakeaway:"Bipolar I = manic episode (7 days or hospitalized or psychotic). Bipolar II = hypomanic episode (4-6 days, no hospitalization) + MDE. Bipolar II is commonly misdiagnosed as MDD  always screen for hypomanic episodes!"}},{id:"bipolar_q2",stem:"A patient with Bipolar I disorder is started on lithium. Lab monitoring should include all of the following EXCEPT:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Thyroid function (TSH)"},{id:"B",text:"Renal function (creatinine, eGFR)"},{id:"C",text:"Serum lithium level"},{id:"D",text:"Liver function tests (ALT, AST)"},{id:"E",text:"ECG (cardiac conduction)"}],correctAnswer:"D",explanation:{correct:"D is CORRECT (the EXCEPT answer). Lithium does NOT require routine liver function monitoring because it is not hepatically metabolized  it is excreted UNCHANGED by the kidneys. Liver function tests are required for valproate (hepatotoxic) and carbamazepine.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT (i.e., TSH IS needed). Lithium causes hypothyroidism in 10-40% of long-term users  check TSH at baseline and q6-12 months.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT (renal function IS needed). Lithium is renally cleared; long-term use causes nephrogenic DI and chronic kidney disease. Check creatinine/eGFR at baseline and q6-12 months.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT (lithium level IS needed). Target 0.6-1.2 mEq/L; check after each dose change, then q3-6 months. Toxicity at >1.5 mEq/L.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT (ECG IS sometimes needed). Lithium can cause T-wave flattening and sinus node dysfunction. ECG especially important in elderly patients or those with cardiac history.",keyTakeaway:"Lithium monitoring: serum level + creatinine/eGFR + TSH. NOT liver enzymes (lithium is not hepatically metabolized  that's valproate and carbamazepine)."}}]},{id:"schizophrenia",name:"Schizophrenia",type:"condition",icd10:"F20",dsmCriteria:{required:"2 of the following  1 month (at least one must be 1, 2, or 3):",symptoms:["1. Delusions","2. Hallucinations","3. Disorganized speech (derailment, incoherence)","4. Grossly disorganized or catatonic behavior","5. Negative symptoms (avolition, alogia, anhedonia, affective flattening, asociality)"],duration:"Continuous disturbance for 6 months (includes prodrome + residual phases)",impairment:"Marked occupational/interpersonal dysfunction",exclusions:"Exclude schizoaffective, mood disorder with psychosis, substance, medical condition"},symptoms:{positive:"Hallucinations (auditory most common: command hallucinations, voices commenting), delusions (persecutory most common), disorganized speech/behavior",negative:"5 As: Avolition, Alogia, Anhedonia, Affective flattening (blunted affect), Asociality",cognitive:"Working memory deficits, processing speed reduction, executive function impairment"},epidemiology:{lifetime:"1%",onset:"Early 20s men; late 20s women",male:"Men earlier onset, worse course"},neurobiology:["Dopamine hypothesis:  D2 in mesolimbic (positive symptoms);  D1 in prefrontal (negative, cognitive)","Glutamate (NMDA) hypothesis: PCP/ketamine (NMDA antagonists) cause ALL symptoms including negative","Serotonin 5-HT2A involvement (explains atypical antipsychotic mechanisms)","Neurodevelopmental model: early prenatal disruption + later stress activation"],antipsychotics:{typical:["Haloperidol","Chlorpromazine","Fluphenazine","Perphenazine","Thioridazine"],atypical:["Clozapine (most effective; agranulocytosis risk)","Olanzapine","Risperidone","Quetiapine","Aripiprazole","Ziprasidone","Asenapine","Lurasidone"],mechanism:"All antipsychotics block D2 receptors; atypicals also block 5-HT2A"},sideEffects:{eps:["Acute dystonia (esp. neck, eyes  treat with diphenhydramine or benztropine)","Parkinsonism","Akathisia (subjective restlessness  treat with propranolol or benzodiazepine)","Tardive dyskinesia (late onset; irreversible; orofacial movements  treat with valbenazine)"],metabolic:["Olanzapine + clozapine: most weight gain, metabolic syndrome","Quetiapine: moderate","Aripiprazole + ziprasidone: weight neutral"],other:["Clozapine: agranulocytosis (requires weekly WBC monitoring initially)","Haloperidol: QTc prolongation","Thioridazine: retinal pigmentation at high doses","Risperidone: highest prolactin elevation among atypicals"]},keyFacts:["Clozapine: most effective antipsychotic (especially for refractory schizophrenia and suicidality), but reserved for treatment-resistant due to agranulocytosis","Tardive dyskinesia: involuntary orofacial movements after long-term dopamine blockade; risk higher with typical antipsychotics; treat with VMAT2 inhibitors (valbenazine, deutetrabenazine)","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome (NMS): fever + rigidity + autonomic instability + altered consciousness; treatment = stop antipsychotic + dantrolene/bromocriptine","Negative symptoms respond poorly to typical antipsychotics; better with atypicals","Maintenance therapy required lifelong to prevent relapse"],questions:[{id:"schiz_q1",stem:'A 21-year-old male is admitted with hearing voices that tell him he is being watched, believing the CIA is controlling his thoughts through his fillings, and speaking in disconnected sentences ("The CIA is the purple moon because television"). He has been like this for 8 months. His urine toxicology is negative. The MOST appropriate first-line pharmacotherapy is:',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Clozapine 25mg titrated to effect"},{id:"B",text:"Lithium 300mg TID"},{id:"C",text:"Risperidone 2-6mg daily"},{id:"D",text:"Sertraline 100mg daily"},{id:"E",text:"Diazepam 5mg TID for agitation"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. First-episode schizophrenia: atypical antipsychotic (second-generation). Risperidone is a commonly used first-line atypical antipsychotic. This patient has positive symptoms (auditory hallucinations, delusions, disorganized speech) for 8 months = meets schizophrenia criteria.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Clozapine is reserved for TREATMENT-RESISTANT schizophrenia (failure of 2 antipsychotics at adequate doses) or persistent suicidality. Risk of agranulocytosis makes it inappropriate as first-line.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Lithium is a mood stabilizer for bipolar disorder. Not indicated for schizophrenia as monotherapy (may be added as adjunct for affective symptoms).",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. SSRIs do not treat psychosis. No depressive episode is described. Starting an antidepressant without an antipsychotic in schizophrenia is inappropriate.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Benzodiazepines may be used short-term for agitation, but they do not treat the underlying psychotic disorder. Not appropriate as primary treatment.",keyTakeaway:"First-episode schizophrenia  atypical antipsychotic (risperidone, olanzapine, aripiprazole, quetiapine). Save clozapine for treatment-resistant cases (2+ failed trials)."}}]},{id:"bpd",name:"Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD)",type:"condition",icd10:"F60.3",dsmCriteria:{required:"Pervasive pattern of instability in interpersonal relationships, self-image, and affects, with marked impulsivity, beginning in early adulthood, 5 of 9:",symptoms:["1. Frantic efforts to avoid real/imagined abandonment","2. Unstable/intense interpersonal relationships alternating between idealization and devaluation (splitting)","3. Identity disturbance: markedly unstable self-image","4. Impulsivity in 2 potentially self-damaging areas","5. Recurrent suicidal behavior/threats/gestures OR self-mutilating behavior","6. Affective instability (intense episodic dysphoria, anxiety, irritability usually lasting hours)","7. Chronic feelings of emptiness","8. Intense/inappropriate anger or difficulty controlling anger","9. Transient stress-related paranoid ideation or severe dissociative symptoms"]},epidemiology:{prevalence:"1-2% general population; 10-20% psychiatric outpatients; 20% inpatients",female:"3:1 in clinical settings (may reflect referral bias)"},etiology:["Linehan's Biosocial theory: emotional sensitivity (biological) + invalidating environment","History of childhood trauma, abuse, neglect in ~70%","Genetic component: heritability ~40%","Amygdala hyperreactivity; prefrontal cortex inhibition failure"],treatment:{firstChoice:"DBT (Dialectical Behavior Therapy)  gold standard",alternatives:["MBT (Mentalization-Based Therapy)","TFP (Transference-Focused Psychotherapy)","Schema Therapy"],pharmacotherapy:"Adjunctive only (mood stabilizers for affective instability, antipsychotics for brief psychotic symptoms). NO FDA-approved medication specifically for BPD.",avoid:"Long-term benzodiazepines (high misuse risk); antidepressants have limited evidence for BPD"},keyFacts:["Splitting: seeing things as all-good or all-bad (idealization  devaluation); primitive defense mechanism","Self-harm/NSSI in BPD is often dissociated from suicide intent  serves to relieve emotional pain (regulate emotions)","Suicide rate: ~10% complete suicide (significant)","Comorbidity: very high with MDD, PTSD, substance use disorders, eating disorders","Prognosis: better than once thought; many achieve remission by 40s with treatment"],questions:[{id:"bpd_q1",stem:`A 26-year-old woman is admitted for non-suicidal self-injury (cutting her arms). She describes her previous therapist as "the most wonderful human on earth" until the therapist went on a 2-week vacation, after which the therapist became "the most cruel and uncaring person I've ever met." This pattern of thinking is best called:`,choices:[{id:"A",text:"Projection"},{id:"B",text:"Splitting"},{id:"C",text:"Reaction formation"},{id:"D",text:"Idealization alone"},{id:"E",text:"Paranoia"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:'B is CORRECT. Splitting (also called "all-or-nothing" thinking in object relations) is the hallmark primitive defense mechanism of BPD: inability to hold ambivalent feelings  the therapist goes from perfect (all-good) to evil (all-bad) when attachment/abandonment fears are triggered. Classic on boards: idealization  vacation/perceived abandonment  devaluation = splitting.',whyNotA:`A is INCORRECT. Projection: attributing one's own unacceptable feelings to someone else ("she doesn't hate me  I hate her"). Not what's happening here.`,whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Reaction formation: converting unacceptable impulse into opposite. Not the mechanism described.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. The combination of idealization + devaluation (switching between extremes) is splitting. Idealization alone is one phase of it.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Paranoia involves unfounded suspicion of harm. While BPD can have transient paranoid ideation, the described pattern specifically represents splitting.",keyTakeaway:"Splitting = all-or-nothing object perception (all-good  all-bad with no integration). Core defense in BPD. Triggered by perceived abandonment. Treatment: DBT (helps tolerate dialectical complexity)."}}]},{id:"substance_use",name:"Substance Use Disorders",type:"condition",icd10:"F10F19",dsmCriteria:{required:"2 of 11 criteria within 12 months:",categories:["Impaired control: using more/longer than intended; unsuccessful efforts to cut down; great deal of time obtaining/using/recovering; craving","Social impairment: failure to fulfill role obligations; continued use despite social/interpersonal problems; giving up activities","Risky use: use in physically hazardous situations; continued use despite knowledge of physical/psychological problem","Pharmacological: tolerance; withdrawal"],severity:"Mild (2-3 criteria) · Moderate (4-5 criteria) · Severe (6 criteria)"},medications:{alcohol:{withdrawal:"CIWA-Ar scale; benzodiazepines (first-line: chlordiazepoxide, diazepam, lorazepam  LORE: Lorazepam, Oxazepam, temazepam, Estazolam for liver disease  no active metabolites)",maintenance:["Naltrexone (-opioid antagonist; reduces craving and reward; hepatotoxic)","Acamprosate (NMDA modulator; reduces protracted withdrawal; renally excreted  safe in liver disease)","Disulfiram (aldehyde dehydrogenase inhibitor; aversive therapy; acetaldehyde buildup = flushing, nausea)"],nutritional:"Thiamine (B1) BEFORE glucose to prevent Wernicke encephalopathy (WE)  Korsakoff syndrome"},opioid:{overdose:"Naloxone (IM/intranasal)  opioid antagonist; repeat q2-3 min; watch for re-narcotization",withdrawal:"Not life-threatening; clonidine (2 agonist) for autonomic symptoms; COWS scale",maintenance:["Methadone (-agonist; long-acting; reduces cravings; regulated program)","Buprenorphine  naloxone (partial -agonist; ceiling effect  safer; Office-Based Opioid Treatment)","Naltrexone (antagonist; monthly injection Vivitrol; good for highly motivated patients)"]},nicotine:["Varenicline (partial nicotinic ACh receptor agonist  most effective)","Bupropion (NRI  also antidepressant)","NRT (patches, gum, lozenge)"]},keyFacts:["Alcohol withdrawal timeline: 6-24h tremors  24-72h seizures  48-96h delirium tremens (DTs)  most dangerous","DTs: fever + tachycardia + agitation + autonomic instability; treat with IV benzodiazepines","Wernicke encephalopathy: confusion + ataxia + ophthalmoplegia (triad); treat with IV thiamine STAT","Korsakoff: anterograde amnesia + confabulation; result of untreated/recurrent Wernicke","CAGE questionnaire: Cut down · Annoyed · Guilty · Eye-opener (2 = likely AUD)","AUDIT-C: 3-item alcohol screening (more sensitive than CAGE)"],questions:[{id:"sud_q1",stem:"A 52-year-old man with chronic alcohol dependence is admitted for pneumonia. He receives IV dextrose before thiamine is given. On day 2, he develops acute confusion, bilateral horizontal gaze palsy, and ataxia. The pathophysiology of this complication is:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Hypoglycemia from impaired gluconeogenesis"},{id:"B",text:"Thiamine deficiency worsened by glucose-driven thiamine consumption, causing hemorrhagic necrosis of the mammillary bodies"},{id:"C",text:"Alcohol withdrawal delirium due to GABA suppression"},{id:"D",text:"Acute bacterial meningitis from immunosuppression"},{id:"E",text:"Hyponatremia from inappropriate ADH secretion"}],correctAnswer:"B",explanation:{correct:"B is CORRECT. This is Wernicke encephalopathy  the classic TRIAD: confusion + ataxia + ophthalmoplegia (eye movement abnormalities). Pathophysiology: thiamine is required for glucose metabolism (pyruvate dehydrogenase complex). Giving glucose WITHOUT thiamine to a thiamine-deficient patient rapidly depletes the remaining thiamine  hemorrhagic necrosis of the mammillary bodies, dorsomedial thalamus, periaqueductal gray.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. The patient received dextrose  hypoglycemia is not the issue. The issue is that glucose without thiamine depletes the remaining thiamine.",whyNotC:"C is INCORRECT. Alcohol withdrawal delirium (DTs) presents with fever, tremors, tachycardia, and occurs 48-96 hours after cessation  a different syndrome without the specific gaze palsy/ataxia triad.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Meningitis would cause meningism (neck stiffness, photophobia, Kernig/Brudzinski signs) and fever. The specific eye movement pattern and ataxia point to Wernicke.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Hyponatremia can cause confusion or seizures but doesn't specifically cause the ophthalmoplegia-ataxia-confusion triad.",keyTakeaway:"ALWAYS give thiamine BEFORE or WITH glucose in any malnourished/alcoholic patient. Wernicke triad: confusion + ophthalmoplegia + ataxia. Untreated  Korsakoff (anterograde amnesia + confabulation  mostly irreversible)."}}]},{id:"grief",name:"Grief, Loss & Bereavement Counseling",type:"modality",founder:"Elisabeth Kbler-Ross (stages); William Worden (tasks); George Bonanno (resilience model)",theoreticalBasis:"Bereavement is a normal human response to loss. Grief counseling helps facilitate the natural grieving process and prevents complicated grief.",stagesKublerRoss:[{stage:"Denial",description:`Shock; protective buffer; "This can't be happening"`},{stage:"Anger",description:`Towards God, doctors, themselves; "Why me? It's not fair"`},{stage:"Bargaining",description:'"If I do X, will you let me live..." negotiating with higher power'},{stage:"Depression",description:"Sadness, withdrawal, preparing for the loss"},{stage:"Acceptance",description:'"It will be okay"; coming to terms with reality'}],wordenTasks:["Accept the reality of the loss","Process the pain of grief","Adjust to a world without the deceased","Find an enduring connection with deceased while embarking on new life"],prolongedGriefDisorder:{dsmDefinition:"DSM-5-TR: intense yearning/longing for deceased + 3 of 8 symptoms of abnormal grief  12 months (6 months for children)",symptoms:["Identity disruption","Marked disbelief about the death","Avoidance of reminders","Intense emotional pain","Difficulty reintegrating","Emotional numbness","Feeling life meaningless without deceased","Intense loneliness"],prevalence:"10-15% of bereaved individuals",treatment:"Complicated Grief Treatment (CGT)  targeted therapy; NOT just antidepressants"},normalVsComplicated:{normal:"Waves of sadness; functional impairment acute but improving; moving through adjustment over time",complicated:"Persistent intense yearning; inability to accept death; function severely impaired >6-12 months; may include suicidality; not progress toward adaptation"},techniques:["Revisiting the loss (imaginal conversations with deceased)","Processing the loss story","Rebuilding life and connection outside grief","Meaning-making (Frankl; posttraumatic growth)","Continuing bonds theory: maintaining transformed relationship with deceased"],questions:[{id:"grief_q1",stem:"A 68-year-old woman lost her husband of 40 years one year ago. She reports daily intense yearning for him, difficulty accepting he is gone, feeling that life has no meaning without him, and has not been able to return to any social activities. She denies significant depressive symptoms. According to DSM-5-TR, this presentation MOST likely represents:",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Normal bereavement  grief is still within expected range"},{id:"B",text:"Major Depressive Disorder triggered by the loss"},{id:"C",text:"Prolonged Grief Disorder"},{id:"D",text:"Adjustment Disorder with depressed mood"},{id:"E",text:"Persistent Depressive Disorder (dysthymia)"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. Prolonged Grief Disorder (DSM-5-TR): intense yearning for deceased + 3 of 8 symptoms of abnormal grief PERSISTING for 12 months after bereavement AND causing functional impairment. She has: intense yearning + difficulty accepting death + meaninglessness + social avoidance  12 months.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. While grief is normal, the duration (12 months), intensity, and functional impairment here exceed what is expected. DSM-5-TR specifically created Prolonged Grief Disorder for this pattern.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. She specifically denies significant depressive symptoms. MDD requires depressed mood and/or anhedonia + 5 SIG-E-CAPS symptoms. Prolonged grief has distinct features (yearning, identity disruption, disbelief) not captured by MDD.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Adjustment disorder: emotional/behavioral symptoms within 3 months of stressor; NOT meeting criteria for another disorder; resolves within 6 months of stressor end (or if stressor ongoing, proportionate). 12 months without improvement exceeds adjustment disorder.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. PDD requires depressed mood for 2 years. The predominant features here are grief-specific (yearning, identity, meaninglessness) rather than persistent depressive mood.",keyTakeaway:"Prolonged Grief Disorder (PGD): 12 months of intense grief-specific symptoms with functional impairment. Distinguished from MDD (grief features, not depressive features predominate) and normal grief (duration + severity)."}}]},{id:"ipt",name:"Interpersonal Therapy (IPT)",type:"modality",founder:"Gerald Klerman & Myrna Weissman (1970s)",theoreticalBasis:"Depression occurs in an interpersonal context. Improving interpersonal functioning relieves depressive symptoms. Based on attachment theory and social roles.",focusAreas:[{area:"Grief",description:"Abnormal/complicated bereavement; facilitating grief process"},{area:"Role Transitions",description:"Major life changes (divorce, retirement, parenthood, diagnosis) causing role adjustment"},{area:"Role Disputes",description:"Conflicts with significant others (spouse, employer, family)"},{area:"Interpersonal Deficits",description:"Social isolation, lack of social skills, difficulty forming relationships"}],phases:[{phase:"Initial (weeks 1-3)",focus:"Assess depression; interpersonal inventory; identify focus area"},{phase:"Middle (weeks 4-9)",focus:"Work on identified interpersonal problem area"},{phase:"Termination (weeks 10-12)",focus:"Review progress; anticipate challenges; maintain gains; recognize self-competence"}],conditions:["Depression (MDD)  especially postpartum depression","Bipolar disorder (adjunct)","Eating disorders (bulimia)","Social anxiety","HIV-related depression"],evidence:"Strong; APA recommended; comparable to CBT in large meta-analyses for MDD.",duration:"1216 sessions (time-limited, structured)",keyFacts:["IPT is present-focused (unlike psychodynamic which explores past)","Not focused on thoughts (unlike CBT)  focuses on relationships and communication","Interpersonal inventory: map of key relationships to identify problems","Particularly effective for postpartum depression","Communication analysis: what the patient said vs. what they felt vs. what they needed"],questions:[{id:"ipt_q1",stem:'A 32-year-old woman develops depression after becoming a mother. She feels she has "lost her identity" and struggles with the transition from career-focused professional to primary caregiver. An IPT therapist would identify this as which focus area?',choices:[{id:"A",text:"Grief"},{id:"B",text:"Role dispute"},{id:"C",text:"Role transition"},{id:"D",text:"Interpersonal deficits"},{id:"E",text:"Social withdrawal"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. Role transition: depression associated with a major life change requiring role adjustment (here: professional identity  motherhood). IPT addresses mourning the old role, adapting to the new role, and building social support for the transition.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. Grief in IPT refers specifically to bereavement following death. No death is described here.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Role dispute involves ongoing conflict with a specific significant other (e.g., disagreements with partner about parenting roles). Here, the issue is her internal adjustment to the transition itself, not a dispute.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Interpersonal deficits applies when there are chronic social isolation problems or lack of close relationships  not triggered by a specific life transition.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Social withdrawal is a symptom rather than an IPT focus area category.",keyTakeaway:"IPT 4 focus areas: Grief (death/loss) · Role Transition (life change) · Role Dispute (interpersonal conflict) · Interpersonal Deficits (chronic isolation). Postpartum depression: best treated with IPT (role transition focus)."}}]},{id:"mindfulness",name:"Mindfulness-Based Interventions (MBSR/MBCT)",type:"modality",founder:"MBSR: Jon Kabat-Zinn (1979); MBCT: Zindel Segal, Mark Williams, John Teasdale (2002)",theoreticalBasis:"MBSR: stress reduction through non-judgmental present-moment awareness. MBCT: combines mindfulness with cognitive therapy to prevent depressive relapse by decentering from ruminative thought patterns.",definitions:{mindfulness:'"Paying attention in a particular way: on purpose, in the present moment, and non-judgmentally" (Kabat-Zinn)',decentering:'Observing thoughts as mental events rather than objective reality ("just a thought")',rumination:"Repetitive, passive focus on negative feelings and their causes  key mechanism in depressive relapse"},programs:[{name:"MBSR",focus:"Stress reduction; chronic pain; medical conditions; 8-week group program",sessions:"8 weekly  2.5 hours + 1 silent retreat day"},{name:"MBCT",focus:"Depression relapse prevention (3+ previous episodes); 8-week structured",evidence:"Reduces relapse by 43% in patients with 3 depressive episodes"}],techniques:["Body scan","Sitting meditation","Mindful movement (yoga)","Walking meditation","3-minute breathing space"],conditions:["MBSR: Chronic pain, stress, anxiety, psoriasis","MBCT: Recurrent MDD (3 episodes)  as effective as antidepressants for maintenance"],evidence:"Strong  MBCT recommended by NICE (UK) for preventing depression relapse. Extensive neuroscience research (cortical thickening, amygdala volume reduction).",keyFacts:["MBCT specifically effective for patients with 3 depressive episodes","8-week group format with daily home practice","Mindfulness in MBCT teaches patients to recognize early depressive relapse warning signs",'"Being mode" vs "doing mode"  dropping into acceptance vs. striving to fix',"Neurobiological: increases prefrontal control of amygdala; increases cortical thickness in insula and prefrontal cortex"],questions:[{id:"mbct_q1",stem:"A 45-year-old woman has had 4 episodes of Major Depressive Disorder. She is currently in remission on sertraline but fears relapse. Evidence-based guidelines recommend which of the following to prevent depressive relapse?",choices:[{id:"A",text:"Continue sertraline indefinitely without additional intervention"},{id:"B",text:"Stop sertraline and start CBT to address cognitive vulnerabilities"},{id:"C",text:"Add MBCT (Mindfulness-Based Cognitive Therapy) as an adjunct"},{id:"D",text:"Refer for psychoanalysis to address underlying character pathology"},{id:"E",text:"Begin lithium augmentation for prophylaxis"}],correctAnswer:"C",explanation:{correct:"C is CORRECT. MBCT is specifically indicated for relapse prevention in MDD with 3 previous episodes (she has 4). Multiple RCTs show MBCT reduces relapse rate by ~43% compared to treatment as usual. NICE guidelines recommend MBCT for recurring depression maintenance.",whyNotA:"A is INCORRECT. While continuing sertraline is appropriate, adding MBCT provides additional evidence-based relapse protection beyond medication alone.",whyNotB:"B is INCORRECT. Stopping sertraline in a patient with 4 episodes of MDD without clear reason is inappropriate  guidelines recommend maintenance treatment for 2+ years or indefinitely after 3 episodes.",whyNotD:"D is INCORRECT. Psychoanalysis has weak evidence for preventing depressive relapse specifically. MBCT is the evidence-based choice.",whyNotE:"E is INCORRECT. Lithium augmentation is appropriate for treatment-resistant MDD or bipolar disorder maintenance. Not indicated here without treatment resistance (she's in remission on sertraline).",keyTakeaway:"MBCT indications: 3 episodes of MDD, currently in remission. Prevents relapse as effectively as antidepressant maintenance. Mechanism: decentering from ruminative patterns that trigger relapse."}}]}];export{e as E};
